eventRemarks: No PILA at actual plot. Shifted to nearest cluster of PILA. Only 5 so did not set up transect, just took WP and notes. Returned on a backpacking trip and completed a transect. PILA 6-22 are along a transect; PILA 1-5 are satellite trees surveyed at a different date.
Old fire: mixed severity firescar ranging from 1-10m. Sloped. Mixed regen, heavy chinquapin

Chilnualna falls, "Wawona Backpack West, UCD plot #41. GPS point @40 pt. 220 0267448 4161767 +/- 1 ft. Castelleja in the 0->50 m and the 50 -> 100 m. The 0 -> -50m range is also unburned. The plot was shifted about 10 m. calculated end point uses 140m from the beginning; should be 140m from the negative end. B in midGPS column for Beginning point is actually in the middle of the transect downslope and 10 ish m to the the east to go through the center of the densest PILA. Then field randomized (2m) along the azimuth. Once clear beetle kill tree - probably also had WPBR (2-3 bole cankers, but a bit confounded by beetles). Overall sparse PILA, but some clumps. Slope at 100m: 31.1. Slope at 40m: 30. Aspect at 100 and 40: 210 and 221, respectively.

Wawona Dome Area. 50m transect gps point: pt. 329 027864 4159758 +/- 1ft. Slope at 50m and 82m: 30 and 31.6. Aspect at 50m and 82m: 159 and 170. Ribes within approx. 50m of plot. Mostly PIMO on ridge above, but transitions to PILA on this slope. Sporadic single tree to clumps of DEPO kill in PIMO above and PILA below plot. Nice view of Wawona Point area. M in mid column indicates that we took a middle GPS point. currently not used but could be

measured 1 SD PILA near 0, -0.2. 1 more similar large PILA more downslope/ negative. 3 more smaller ~30-40 DBH 20 ish height near/ on negative side. No live PILA. High severity in plot. A few live PIPO within 40-50m. 50-400+ all dead trees. A few PILA trees, saplings, seedlings on the way down (no WPBR). From Emma Sayre notes: End info: slope is 27.5, aspect 211. WP 258 ON 66SI +/- 0ft. Nothing live, dead CADE @55.5 from end, next closest is 384. Some other SD but nothing identifiable. High severity burn.

North Dome. This is a steep plot for 50m but there were so few trees we also extended width-wise. Pedicularis in 0-50m. Pika fire burned most of understory but generally not overstory in this area. A fews trees scortched/ torched. Understory 90% burned- black charcoal. 2 large mature PILA upslope, 2 medium PILA downslope (past our balloon plot which is already way past 200m). Waypoint at 50m: pt. 301 0274168 4182728 +/- 11 ft. Waypoint at 100m: pt 302 0274193 4182774 +/- 9ft. Waypoint at 150m: pt 303 0274212 4182799 +/-10ft. Slope at 50, 100, 150 and 200: 23.4, 20.4, 19.5 and 21.3. Aspect at 50, 100, 200: 287, 231, 287 and 294. Balloon on both ends of the transect/dumbell shaped.

Cool wolf lichen? w/  brown fruitng bodies falling in plot. Chose direction to avoid drainage and resulting aspect/ elevation change. No PILA on route down creek or on this slope w/ this aspect. Opposite side of the creek has a stand of PIMO and many on ridge. 10+ PIMO in a clump 450-500m away (near creek junction) with some flag/ flagging, scattered beetle kill 3-5 tree out of 100 ish. have GPS point for 50m, only calc for 200m.

No mature PILA or saplings or seedlings. Lots of ABMA seedlings on opposite slope (NW facing) but no regen of any species on this side.  No mature PILA observed with bions within 500m to completed as a high severity protocol. Did a grid search in a 200 x 100m plot for PILAsaplings plus rescanned for mature with binos. Fire recent `2-5 years ago. Small ABCO dead, shrubs resprouting. No sign of older dead PILA. Waypoint at 50m: pt. 129 0261251 4207274 +/- 5ft. Aspect at 50m: 18.8. Slope at 50m: 18.8. Plot elevation at 50: 7589 ft.

Plot was moved ~30m downslope from center of point to capture more PILA. Field randomized 3m. Very small stream through plot @ ~30 Dout, disappears before 40 Dside, possible spring near tree 3&4. Understory much drier past the 50m and downslope. Unofficial survey to 200m found 2 more PILA just outside plot one -50m dSide and one over 200m dOut. 6-7 PILA on the right (positive) side, but some too close to the trail (within the trail buffer). A lot of MECH from wind. Lots of yellowing needles--maybe seasonal. Plot waypoint at 50m: pt. 269 0268252 4180448 +/- 1 ft. Slope at 50 and 108: 25.5 and 23.9. Aspect at 50 and 108: 112 and 188. Trees 1, 15, 19, 20, 26, 27 , 28 and 31 were within 10m of a trail on the left (negative) side. Survey includes tree 1, which is 13.7m before the GPS start on the transect, making the full surveyed length 123m while the distance between gps start and gps end is 108m. GPS points at 0m and 108m, but trees surveyed out to -13.7 and -108.9m

Plot was randomly selected, but supposed to be in a high severity area. In reality, the plot was unburned. At 150m the transect ran into a rock and plunged into a creek bed. There were about 5-6 PILA along the steep creek banks, but all within the 10m creek buffer. They would have been around 150-160m Dout on the negative side towards the stream. This area also had PIMO with possible WPBR. Slope 20.1 at the start, but steeper at the 150 end about 22 degrees. Aspect was 59 magnetic = 61.5 true at the start and 46 magnetic = 58.5 true at the 150 end. Point 210 was the beginning of the trasect. Point 211 was the tree closest to the 150 end. Point 213 is the farthest point away from point 211, so should probably be considered the negative end. calculated end point uses 200m from the beginning; should be 200m from the -50m end. B in midGPS column for Beginning point is actually in the middle of the transect. Last few trees might be a little balloony.

Near development, shifted plot 10m from slash pile and 45m from road. Ribes within plot; more on the right side. Possible low severity fire; burn scars 0.5-2m high. Little regen, lots of litter and some downed logs.

Spring in plot near -7m DOut and bear poop; no cone producing trees in or near plot. Seed dispersal--wind and/or bear? No ribes, pedicularis or castelleja observed within the plot, but noted within 100m on the way to the plot. Bear/climber trail to Hetch Hetchy Dome is much better than the way we took down! Departure from trail noted on GPS/Avenza. A lot of old standing dead and down could be PILA, but PILA and PIPO bark looks similar in this plot and too old to assess for WPBR anyway. Seven PILA seedlings throughout the plot. Regen from dead trees? bears? One big tree just before the plot in poor health.

Slope: 20 average, 24 up, 16 down. Aspect: 42 beg, 19 end. Spring through plot at ~46m dOut. Goes underground through transect, more present upslope (+dside), pops out 8 or so meters downslope. Some large trees have yellowing tops/branch tips or old dead branch tips could be ipps beatles.ABCO, PSME, and PILA seedlings growing around most big PILA andd around the plot. Beautiful view of YOSE high country on hike in. A few sketchy snags in and near plot. Next live clump in 150-200+m ~12 live PILA, no signs of WPBR, DBH 100+, heights 50+m
After 50 meters, sharp ravine, 380 meter away from 0 spotted 1 mature PILA with cones, heavy burn area, CEIN heavy, extremely hard to navigate

Plot on slope with thick head high white thorn and CEIN; hard to move through. High severity burn. Lots of downed logs and SD. 3 PILA seedlings found right before beginning of transect. Saplings and seedlings mostly found in clearings near SD. Closest stand of PILA is 60m behind the start of the transect on a different aspect, and on other side of a ravine. PILA regen happening in open clearings and ravines. May not be spatially independent from 16; based off same point.
SUS activity toward 50 and 50 meters Dside. Just outside of 50 there is a tree with a Dtop. Lots of PILA regen. May not be spatially independent from 15; based off same point

Handful of very burnt charcoal that could be anything imaginable. Transect ran cross slop on hill side that slants into flat area filled with whitethorn. Halfway of transect waypoint: #254 11S 0257338 UTM 4190782 +/- 0 ft. End of plot aspect: 172 degrees. End of plot slope: 8.7 degrees.

Low severity fire, not much understory.Somewhat on ridge. Close to road ~40 m. Moved plot to get SPs and away from road -> original plot was in middle of road. Large adult SP, ABCO, PIPO, CADEs. Regen SPs, CADEs, little ABCO. Downed logs. Slash piles ~20 m from the start of the 0.
plot photos Jenny's phone 11:53 smaller holes see Jenny's phone 1:37 on 6/27/23 for pictures; slope: 19.5 @ end 16.3 @ start

Trasect starts in high severity CECO clearning, but 51-100m is forest with more surviving mature trees. In general area surrounding the plot, a lot of the largest PILA are dead. Biggest sapling cluster under our biggest dead tree. Lots of seedlings (very small to 0.9m height), ABCO and PIPO too.
Lots of regen - PILA, ABCO. Streams on both sides ~100m away. Shaded area. Hipso died in plot so heights are estimated.

Seedling count in 150-200m column is only for 150-161m. Slope @0 is 9, @160 is 8.7. Aspect @0 is 114, @160 is 162.  Plot is mostly low severity to moderate with small patches of high severity. High severity patch on the negative end of the transect. Chose azimuth based on PILA. A lot of PIPO and CADE regen (along wiht some PILA), lots in 100-150m region. Dry drainage crossed transect around 100m. Species shifts towards those that like water past there.

5 mature large PILA (DBH 100+, height 40+, all but 1 with cones) just outside plot (dSide +73 and beyond). 1 more similar ~25DBH SD PILA (dOut -10); One ~80DBH DD PILA propped against ABCO #259 on associated trees survey.

Moss canyon; 0.8-0.9m and shorter seedlings scattered throughout the plot. Observed one big mature PILA on the hike in from the drainage. Lots of beautiful cones--possible source for many of the seedlings and saplings in the plot. Also, 4 mature PILA with tiny cones (immature) 30-45m towards the creek. calculated end point uses 71m from the beginning; should be 71m from the negative end. B in midGPS column for Beginning point is actually in the middle of the transect.

Mostly large SD Btop PIPOS. Lots of PIPO regen around, lots of downed logs. High severity burn. Closest stand of live about 3 mature PILA 64m away @ 336 degrees. Another cluster of trees with at least 1 mature 156m away at 20 degrees. Black oak and PIPO in 100-200m. No PILA seedlings/saplings/mature trees in transect. No PILA cones on ground.

HetchHetchyNearTarn. 305 @ beg 336 @ end, creek about 30 m away, parallel to the transect castelleja found in 0-50 m, pedicularis found, regen seedlings and saplings of PIPO, ABCO, CADE more common, some PILA seedline especially from 50 - 70m dout; topography is weird because plot is in a depression. So choosing cross - slope is challenging. stopped at ~ 70m dout due to drop in elevation to grassy area with PIPO and CADE. Then surveyed in other direction to capture 2 more PILA. Dumbell shaped. Currently calculates the positive endpoint correctly ( we think), but need to back-calculate the negative endpoint based on the distance. Worth looking at with tree data points. Position, DBH and height estimated for some trees, but likely good estimates as we were close.

PILA locations estimated using compass, hypsometer, and trigonometry. Only did associated species on the negative (left) side because otherwise too time consuming. Balloon on both ends of the transect. One end has two GPS trees while the other has trees with estimated position based on trig.

Lots of poison oak; balloon plot around 200m further across a drainage. Did not assess the area in between for ribes and seedlings due to poison oak. Convex hull likely ok for area, at least for large PILA, but may want to consider using 2 smaller transects for area for small PILA.
Slope(@0): 6.3. Slope(@179): 8.2. Aspect(@0): 14. Aspect(@179): 345. Random plot. Shifted to capture more PILA. Lots of CEIN. Saw a rattlensnake!
No ribes, slope 13.9 @ beg 7.4 @ end, aspect 306@ beg 346@ end

Field width is actually 40m on one side and 50m on the other, but entered as 45m. Lots of dead and downs. Tons of regen -> CADE, ABCO, PILA, Quercus. Open canopy; exposed mountainside. Low severity fire approximately 20 years ago. Group of seedlings and saplings ranging 0-1.5 m tall. Approx 50 in the 35-40 meter belt (d left), d out 28-50 m 20+ sap and 30+ seedling.

Based on Avenza, shifted across the creek onto FS land. Opposite aspects but similar elevation. Across creek (in private property) more PIPO seedlings/saplings (more dense).  From 150-180, very dense PIPO seedlings and saplings. Stopped @ 180 due to property boundry line and PIPO too dense to see. Did quick visual survey from 0 -> -20 and also found no PILA.3 mature PILA w/ cones. Closest big dead top 232 m to the side the of the transect. No other WPBR symptoms. Slope at 50 is 7. Aspect at 50 is 169. On data seet: 2-5 similar dead snags, but unclear whether PIPO or PILA. The angular error between the GPS and calculated end points is very high - maybe look at the angle without the magnetic adjustment, or calculate the apparent azimuth based on the beginning and end GPS points.

lots of regen, PIPO, PILA, some CADE, little to no ABCO some Doug Fir, Fire was high sev some time ago, lots of downed logs, big healthy PILA here, adjusted plot to other side of road to avoid campsite

Aspect was 334 facing away from river and 92 toward river. Started off GPSing individuals because no dense cluster of PILA nearby. Went back and set up transect where we found the 3 PILAs. One tree (PILA4) is some 300-400m away, across a road, on a different aspect. Likely should not be part of plot but is fully assessed.

Off USFS road near Fish Camp; very brushy, steep, fallen logs. Moderate fire severity with regeneration. Soil type is decomposed granite and organics and about 5% rock. This was the first training plot. The transect extends 44m to the edge of a creek. The rest of the plot is a messy balloon. Area should probably be the convex hull.

This is the direction we were supposed to go due to randomization, but road cut cliffs (over 40 degrees) present a safety hazard. 0 to -100 had PSME, CADE, QUKE, PIPO, PILA seedlings, saplings, and mature trees. Calculate a positive end point using length of 20m; calculate the negative end using the negative length.

Slope: 5 beg, 13.1 end. Aspect: 36 beg, 16 end. many seedlings ABCO, lots of PIPO and PILA. At least one PILA seedling w WPBR. CEIN has scale and spittlebugs. A lot of PIPO regen near the random point but not so many PILA, so shifted plots ~ 100 m to capture more PILA.

We did associated trees and understory at original point 60m from trail and underneath a rocky outcrop, but no PILA. Tree 1 is the closest PILA we could see. Possible Dend and or ipps activity in PIJE on the ridge above the plot. 14-15 more PILA on the other side of ridge (opposite aspects) see note on phone. Area for this plot is listed as NA because this plot does not really fit  within our study design. These PILA would be high quality iNat observations, but really do not meet criteria for the study. Area could be calculated as the convex hull between the GPS'ed PILAs, but the area between these points is far to vast to assume there are zero sugar pines in between.

Slope: 24 start, 21 end. Aspect: 76 start, 46 end. Tree 5 possible recovered tree from WPBR? Tree 6 just outside plot to side near creek, tree 2 just outside negative, ~3 other saplings a bit further. Lots of PILA seedlings <1m. RIRO in plot - creek ~10m past downslope plot edge.

Rim of the world upper. randomly selected direction cross slope, but hit drainage, rest of the area covered in CEIN 40%, QUCH 10%, QUKE 30%, RIRO 1%, ARVI 6%, TODI 2%, PSME 5%, PIPO 2%, PILA 21% in this cleaing we also see quite a few PSME & PIPO saplings. There may be some PILA saplings too but we're too far away. All PILA assessed from distance, beetle assessment based on canopy only dbh estimated height/bearing/dout measured from road. Slope: 31 @ 0 34 @ 50; aspect: 295@ 0 39@ 50. This was the Rim of the World upper plot in Stanislaus National Forest. Jenny did associated trees and veg survey alone at the high severity location. The nearest trees were well over 500m away, but surveyed with binoculars and position estimated with trig.

First plot. Shifted plot towards creek to avoid slash pile. Plot 30-40m from a small creek. 2 PILA about 40m tall not sampled due to being within 1-2m from the creek and across the creek. Very high species richness due to creek. A few suspicous old dead branches, but none clearly due to WPBR.

Pedicularis present, seedling near 100m Dout, 15m Dside has WPBR, height 0.3, photos @ 12:04pm. Lots of seedlings, 2-5 more saplings just past 147m. PIPO and PIJE cones in plot. High severity over ridge. Low to mixed severity in 0-100m. Mixed to high severity 100-147m. Near creek with water.
Lots of PILA regen. Lots of downed trees. Saw RIRO on way to the plot. Observed PILA with WPBR symptoms (Dtop, entry point) on way to plot.

Yosemite Wilderness. Very dense CEIN and Prunus on the way to the plot. Castelleja and RIRO on the way to the plot. Lots of PIPO, ABCO, some CADE (very burned with bark sloughing). PILA seedling about 53m out on the transect with 2 flags--probably NECH. Also 0.9m tall seedling close to last ABCO (Dout about 49.1).

Actual transect was 50m, but added visual extension to make it 212m. Slope changed from 18 to 7 throughout transect. Aspect changed from 351 to 344. Elevation changed from 5230 to 1594m. Cow poop on trail near plot.  PILA seedlings (at least 2 with probable WPBR). ABCO, PSME, and PIPO regen. Trees 1-4, 22 on ridge/just over with aspect closer to 1700. Trees 16 and 17 on rock outcrop. Dout ~58, there is a clump of 4 SD broken PILA with 50-70 DBH. Lots of CEIN and CUFO in understory. Surveyed for saplings in 1st 50m. Only rounded 0.9+ saplings to 1m due to sparse PILA and saplings. Next mature tree alongs transect 214m from last tree (Dout ~426m). Trees 21-45 are an estimated balloon near camp; closest PILA to plot trees and lower sawmill plot. Tree 43 is 5m towards road from clump; no WP. Castelleja in and out of the plot. Needed trig to determine some relative tree locations.

Actual plot roadside assessment: Lots of CEIN, QUKE resprouts. Visual percent cover from road: 7% rock, 30% QUKE, 65% CEIN. Mature SD: PSME, ABCO, CADE, some PILA and PIPO. Replanting PILA seedlings. No WPBR, no lives trees. WP: 85. Original UTM: 0281780, 4191531. Accuracy: 0. Slope: 13. Aspect: ~343. *Moved plot: slope @ 0m = 7, 50m=12, 200m=9.6. Aspect @ 0m=306, 50m = 294, 200m=293. Elevation changed to 1534m at the end. High severity area. PILA seedlings near trees 1 and 2. No secondary hosts. RIRO near trees 1 and 2 also all over plot. Pretty closed canopy. Transect listed as 200m, but probably closer to 250-300m.

Stream before 0m and a very small stream at 34m. Mixed burn with high severity fading to low severity as we progress to 50m. Sharp slope east that becomes level at transect. Steep ravine after 110m, so we used hipso to estimate distance/height and estimated DBH of inaccessible PILAS in the distance. Transect length is up to about 150m on the left side, but the trees in 110m-150m section on the right are primarily estimated. Beyond 150m all trees are estimated.
No sugar pine regen, plenty of cedar and white fir. Very tall ABCOs with closed canopies, not a lot of sunlight shining through clearing.Lots of downed logs

Smith Mountain South. Position on ridge makes one azimuth better for a 200m run, so we didn't randomize. Full of whitethorn, so no proper sapling sweep, but we walked the 200m and saw no emergent saplings. Two trees noted at the bottom would be in plot. Missed a smaller 40ish DBH, 25m height PILA, but it was over 50m to the side.
Smith Mountain Peak. We randomized direction of azimuth because topography and safety looked similar on both sides. Lots of whitethorn 50-200m.
Slope said 5-7 degrees. Mixed severity fire approx 10yr. Tons of whitethorn. Seedlings typically in open areas.
High severity burn throughout area- the plot itself is moderate and low severity

adjusted plot due to no PILA in original plot, relatively flat area with same aspect as original plot, lots of PILA adults with not much regen, lots of manzanita, slope steepens 50+ meters dside left by a lot.

Lots of dead and down PILAS. Road nearby >200m away. Medium severity burn 10yrs ago. Dense PILA cluster 480m dsideR on a ridge. PIPO dominant. Heavy PIPO regen, no PILA regen. PILAS spread out 100+ m on both sides of transect; only 3 ~120m dside
Glacier Point Road Closure. 1 old dead top near plot that looks sus. High severity fire near the plot. ~1m gap between 1st 50m and 2nd 50 m - adjusted in field

Lower grouse creek. Beginning of plot (50-100m) is pretty unburned, but there are a few high severity patches nearby. Spring just past the 50m. All large trees had baby cones. Original notes give estimates for the 30th and 31st tree, but this must be the 36th and 37th tree, respectively (filling in data sheet that way): 30th tree was ~70m out +20m side, DBH ~ 60, height ~30, no beetles, symptoms or flags, No DTOP, 98% live ~0m fire scar, cones. 31st tree ~80m out, 30m side, similar size to above, cones, no symptoms, other trees much farther mabe 50m +, different stand.

End waypoint on 66si. Slope at 0: 30.1, at 50: 25, at 150: 24. Aspect at 0: 225, at 50: 225: at 150: 228. Pretty open -- lots of rocks. Sloped; ravine around 130m (no water). Mix of big SD and live trees. Mostly PILA/PIPO regen. Epic view! Plot seems to be on the edge of a high severity zone, but most of plot is low severity with small HS patches. Saw cool hawk or falcon!

PILA seedlings within 50m of transect and on the way up about 100m out, 90m to the side. One mature PILA 160m from tree 8 @28 degrees, about 100 DBH, 30 height, yellowing needles, ipps, thinning top. One other mature PILA similar distance further upslope, no symptoms, 55m out, 90m side. 13-15 mature PILA in a clump right next to Return Creek about 230m downslope from the 50m. 6-7 large sapling and mature PILA in a stand about 120-170m downslope from 50m end running past the 0 end captured in balloon plot. Except 2 50-80 DBH, 30 height, with cones, healthy, 99% live, 1 about 30m downslope and toward trail from tree 10, 1 near point 361 (end of the stand). -40 to +106m for main transect survey, remaining trees in very messy balloon on right side of transect towards creek.

UCSB final plot! National Gaucamole Day!! Started in a very slight ravine. Pretty open with some CEIN patches. ~60m from 120 road. PILA/CADE/ some ABCO regen. Lots of PILA regen! Nice open space, large trees are far apart; sunlight gets through to floor. DIstinction between seedlings in 50 vs 100 not made so added altogether in 50 m. Start of the plot slope is 7.8 and end of the plot slope is 3.4. The beginning of plot aspect is 164 degrees and ending aspect is 165 degrees.
